# Jam Session AR Integration - Walkthrough

The Jam Session (Live Band) feature has been fully integrated into the existing AirJam AR player interfaces, providing a seamless and immersive multiplayer experience.

## Key Accomplishments

### 1. Seamless AR Integration
- **Existing UIs Reused:** Jam sessions now use the high-quality standalone [piano-player.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/piano-player.html) and [drums-player.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/drums-player.html) pages instead of separate practice interfaces.
- **Bi-directional Sync:** Notes played locally via hand tracking are broadcast to all participants. Remote notes are played through your local speakers and visualized on your instrument.

### 2. Robust Room Management
- **Room Validation:** Implemented a `/check_room` backend endpoint. Users can no longer join arbitrary rooms; they must enter a valid 6-character code generated by a host.
- **Race Condition Fixed:** The server now tracks created rooms immediately, ensuring that clients can join even before the host connects their WebSocket. This resolves the "Invalid room code" error for early joiners.
- **Dynamic Connection:** Integrated a centralized [jam-core.js](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/jam-core.js) to manage WebSocket connections and shared state across all player pages.

### 3. Remote Access via Ngrok
- **Public URL:** The system automatically detects and uses your public ngrok tunnel for jam sessions, enabling users on different networks to join.
- **Active Link:** `https://unsurpliced-qualitatively-tressa.ngrok-free.dev`

### 4. Visual Refinements
- **Idle Flashes Disabled:** In the piano player, the expanding "hit" circles are now suppressed in freeplay/jam mode. They only appear when a specific song is actively playing, as requested.

### 5. Player Connection Feedback
- **Join/Leave Toasts:** The app now automatically displays a toast notification (e.g., "Player joined: anonymous") when someone enters or leaves your jam room.
- **Improved UX:** You no longer have to wonder if your partner is connected; the system provides immediate visual feedback.

### 6. Bi-directional Audio Sync
- **Cross-Instrument Sound:** Piano players now automatically load and play drum samples when their partner hits a drum. Drum players now have a built-in synth to play back piano notes.
- **WebSocket Fix:** Corrected a port conflict that was preventing player pages from connecting to the jam server. This ensures that audio is broadcast and received correctly on both ends.

## Final Testing Instructions

1. **Start Servers:** Ensure all backends are running via [./start.sh](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/start.sh).
2. **Host a Session:**
   - Open [instruments.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/instruments.html).
   - Click **Jam Session** → **Host Session**.
   - Copy the 6-letter room code (e.g., `XJ1234`).
   - Pick **Piano** or **Drums** to enter the AR studio.
3. **Join a Session (Remote/Local):**
   - Open the ngrok URL or [instruments.html](file:///Users/aniruddhmodi/Documents/PycharmProjects/AirPlay/airplay%202/instruments.html) in another tab.
   - Click **Jam Session** → **Join a room**.
   - Enter the 6-letter code and click **Join**.
   - Pick an instrument to start jamming together!
4. **Verification:**
   - Play a note in one tab → should hear it and see the visual feedback (key/drum flash) in the other tab.
   - Notice that the piano "hit flashes" only appear when you've loaded and started a song.

